EMERGING INFECTIOUS DISEASES, VOLUME 3, NUMBER 4
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
Date: Fri, 31 Oct 1997 11:53:37 -0500
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>

The October-December, Volume 3, Number 4, issue of CDC's journal EMERGING
INFECTIOUS DISEASES (EID) is now available.
Special Issue on Emerging Foodborne Pathogens
A. The National Conference on Emerging Foodborne Pathogens: Implications
and Control, March 24-26, 1997, Alexandria, Virginia, USA. Infectious
Disease as an Evolutionary Paradigm, J. Lederberg
B. Factors that Influence the Emergence or Reemergence and Dissemination
of Microbial Foodborne Pathogens and Human Disease
1. Emerging Foodborne Diseases: An Evolving Public Health Challenge, R.V.
Tauxe
2. Emergence of New Pathogens as a Function of Changes in Host
Susceptibility, J.G. Morris and M. E.Potter
3. Chronic Sequelae of Foodborne Disease, J.A. Lindsay
4. Public, Animal, and Environmental Health Implications of Aquaculture,
E.S. Garrett, C. Lima dos Santos, and M.L. Jahncke
5. Produce Handling and Processing Practices, L.R. Beuchat
6. The Impact of Consumer Demands and Trends on Food Processing, D.L. Zink
7. Impact of Changing Consumer Lifestyles on the Emergence/Reemergence of
Foodborne Pathogens, J.E. Collins
C. Identifying and Anticipating New Foodborne Microbial Hazards

1. Historical Overview of Key Issues in Food Safety, E.M. Foster
2. Quantitative Risk Assessment: An Emerging Tool for Emerging Foodborne
Pathogens, A.M. Lammerding
3. Communicating Foodborne Disease Risk, B. Fischhoff and J.T. Downs
4. Animal Diseases of Public Health Importance, G.D. Orriss
5. Foodborne Disease Control: A Transnational Challenge, F.K. KÃ¤ferstein,
Y. Motarjemi, and D.W. Bettcher
D. Controlling Emerging Foodborne Microbial Hazards
1. Consumer Concerns: Motivating to Action, C.M Bruhn
2. Identifying and Controlling Emerging Foodborne Pathogens: Research
Needs, R.L. Buchanan
3. Maximizing the Usefulness of Food Microbiology Research, T.A. Roberts
4. Epidemiology and Detection as Options for Control of Viral and Parasitic
Foodborne Disease, L-A. Jaykus
5. Quantitative Microbiology: A Basis for Food Safety, T.A. McMeekin, J.
Brown, K. Krist, D. Miles, K. Neumeyer, >D.S. Nichols, J. Olley, K.
Presser, D.A. Ratkowsky, T. Ross, M. Salter, and S. Soontranon
E. Strategies for Mobilizing Resources for Rapid Response to Emerging
Foodborne Microbial Hazards
1. Strategies for Rapid Response to Emerging Foodborne Microbial Hazards,
J. Majkowski
2. Foodborne Illness: Implications for the Future, R.L. Hall
F. Dispatches
Vero Cytotoxin-Producing Escherichia coli O157 Outbreaks in England and
Wales, 1995: Phenotypic Methods and Genotypic Subtyping, G.A. Willshaw,
H.R. Smith, T. Cheasty, P.G. Wall, and B. Rowe
Genetic Polymorphism Among Cryptosporidium parvum Isolates: Evidence of Two
Distinct Human Transmission Cycles, M.M. Peng, L. Xiao, A.R. Freeman, M.J.
Arrowood, A.A. Escalante, A.C. Weltman, C.S.L. Ong, W.R. Mac Kenzie, A.A.
Lal, and C.B. Beard
G. Commentary
Irradiation Pasteurization of Solid Foods: Taking Food Safety to the Next
Level, M.T. Osterholm and M.E. Potter
H. Letters
Non-O157 Shiga Toxin-Producing Escherichia coli Infections in Europe, A.
Caprioli, A.E. Tozzi, G. Rizzoni, and H. Karch
The Taxonomy of Cyclospora, W.C. Marquardt
Reply to W.C. Marquardt, N.J. Pieniazek and B.L. Herwaldt
I. News and Notes
CDC/USDA/FDA Foodborne Diseases Active Surveillance Network (FoodNet)
1998 International Emerging Infectious Disease Conference
Errata
